<worksheet xml:id="lt3-practice-quiz">
<title>Learning Target 3: Linear Patterns</title>
<objectives>
<ul>
<li>I can recognize and identify key characteristics of a linear pattern represented in a table, graph, equation, or application.</li>
<li>I can translate between different representations.</li>
</ul>
</objectives>
<page>
<exercise xml:id="lt3-pattern">
<title>Is the Pattern Linear?</title>
<introduction>
<p>Consider the following pattern of blocks.</p>
<image width="95%">
<shortdescription>Five cases of a growing block pattern in two rows: 6, 8, 10, 12, and 14 blocks.</shortdescription>
<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="lt3-pattern-blocks">
<diagram dimensions="(660,180)" margins="5">
<coordinates bbox="(-1,-2,48,4)">
<repeat parameter="case=1..5">
<repeat parameter="col=0..case+1">
<repeat parameter="row=0..1">
<rectangle center="(10*(case-1)+col, row)" dimensions="(0.85,0.85)" fill="mediumpurple" stroke="black"/>
</repeat>
</repeat>
<label anchor="(10*(case-1)+2, -1.4)" alignment="center">
<m>\text{Case } ${case}</m>
</label>
</repeat>
</coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image>
</introduction>
<task workspace="1.25in">
<statement>
<p>Explain why the pattern is linear.</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
The cases have
<m>6, 8, 10, 12, 14</m>
blocks. The count increases by the same amount,
<m>2</m>
blocks, from each case to the next. Because the rate of change is constant, the pattern is linear.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
<task workspace="1in">
<statement>
<p>How many blocks will be in case 8?</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
Continuing to add
<m>2</m>
each case: case 6 has
<m>16</m>
, case 7 has
<m>18</m>
, and case 8 has
<m>20</m>
blocks.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
<task workspace="1.25in">
<statement>
<p>
Find a linear equation that gives the number of blocks
<m>y</m>
for case
<m>x</m>
.
</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
The number of blocks increases by
<m>2</m>
per case, so the slope is
<m>2</m>
. Working backward, case
<m>0</m>
would have
<m>4</m>
blocks, so the y-intercept is
<m>4</m>
. The equation is
<m>y = 2x + 4</m>
. Check: case
<m>3</m>
gives
<m>2(3)+4 = 10</m>
blocks, which matches.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
</exercise>
</page>
<page>
<exercise xml:id="lt3-graph" workspace="1.5in">
<title>Find the Equation of the Graph</title>
<statement>
<p>Given the linear graph below, find an equation that matches it. Verify that your equation is correct by checking that it matches the line at two points.</p>
<image width="45%">
<shortdescription>A line crossing the y-axis at 2 and passing through the point 4 comma 4.</shortdescription>
<prefigure xmlns="https://prefigure.org" label="lt3-line-graph">
<diagram dimensions="(300,300)" margins="5">
<definition>f(x) = (1/2)*x + 2</definition>
<coordinates bbox="(-1,-1,7,7)">
<grid-axes xlabel="x" ylabel="y" hticks="(0,1,6)" vticks="(0,1,6)"/>
<graph function="f" stroke="blue" thickness="2"/>
<point p="(0,2)" size="4" fill="blue"/>
<point p="(4,4)" size="4" fill="blue"/>
</coordinates>
</diagram>
</prefigure>
</image>
<p>
(The points
<m>(0,2)</m>
and
<m>(4,4)</m>
are marked to help you.)
</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
The line crosses the y-axis at
<m>(0,2)</m>
, so
<m>b=2</m>
. From
<m>(0,2)</m>
to
<m>(4,4)</m>
the line rises
<m>2</m>
and runs
<m>4</m>
, so the slope is
<m>\frac{2}{4} = \frac{1}{2}</m>
. The equation is
<m>y = \frac{1}{2}x + 2</m>
.
</p>
<p>
Check at
<m>(0,2)</m>
:
<m>\frac{1}{2}(0)+2 = 2</m>
. Check at
<m>(4,4)</m>
:
<m>\frac{1}{2}(4)+2 = 4</m>
. Both points match, so the equation is correct.
</p>
</answer>
</exercise>
</page>
<page>
<exercise xml:id="lt3-table-nonlinear" workspace="1.5in">
<title>Could This Table Be Linear?</title>
<statement>
<p>Determine whether the following table could represent linear change. Explain your answer in writing.</p>
<tabular>
<row bottom="medium">
<cell>
<m>x</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>0</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>1</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>2</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>3</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>4</m>
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>
<m>y</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>5</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>10</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>20</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>40</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>80</m>
</cell>
</row>
</tabular>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
It is not linear. As
<m>x</m>
increases by
<m>1</m>
each time,
<m>y</m>
changes by
<m>+5</m>
, then
<m>+10</m>
, then
<m>+20</m>
, then
<m>+40</m>
. The rate of change is not constant (the values double each step), so the table cannot represent linear change.
</p>
</answer>
</exercise>
<exercise xml:id="lt3-table-linear" workspace="1.5in">
<title>Could This Table Be Linear?</title>
<statement>
<p>Determine whether the following table could represent linear change. Explain your answer in writing.</p>
<tabular>
<row bottom="medium">
<cell>
<m>x</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>0</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>1</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>2</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>3</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>4</m>
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>
<m>y</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>4</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>10</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>16</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>22</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>28</m>
</cell>
</row>
</tabular>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
It could be linear. As
<m>x</m>
increases by
<m>1</m>
each time,
<m>y</m>
increases by
<m>6</m>
every time. The rate of change is constant at
<m>6</m>
, which is the defining characteristic of a linear pattern. (An equation would be
<m>y = 6x + 4</m>
.)
</p>
</answer>
</exercise>
</page>
<page>
<exercise xml:id="lt3-battery">
<title>Charging a Phone Battery</title>
<introduction>
<p>
The following table gives the percent charge of a phone battery
<m>t</m>
minutes after it is plugged in.
</p>
<tabular>
<row bottom="medium">
<cell>
<m>t</m>
(minutes)
</cell>
<cell>
<m>0</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>5</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>10</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>15</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>20</m>
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>charge (%)</cell>
<cell>
<m>20</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>30</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>40</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>50</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>60</m>
</cell>
</row>
</tabular>
</introduction>
<task workspace="1.5in">
<statement>
<p>
The data appears linear. Find an equation for the battery percentage
<m>P</m>
after
<m>t</m>
minutes.
</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
The charge increases by
<m>10</m>
percentage points every
<m>5</m>
minutes, a rate of
<m>2</m>
percent per minute. At
<m>t=0</m>
the charge is
<m>20\%</m>
. So
<m>P = 2t + 20</m>
.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
<task workspace="1.75in">
<statement>
<p>
Suppose we later check the phone at
<m>t = 30</m>
minutes and find the charge is only
<m>74\%</m>
. Does this match the linear pattern, or does it suggest the charging may not always be linear? Explain your reasoning.
</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
The linear equation predicts
<m>P = 2(30) + 20 = 80\%</m>
at
<m>t=30</m>
. The actual charge of
<m>74\%</m>
is lower than the linear prediction. This suggests the charging is not always linear: as a battery fills up, charging tends to slow down, so the percentage grows more slowly than the early linear rate would predict.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
</exercise>
</page>
<page>
<exercise xml:id="lt3-pool">
<title>Draining a Pool</title>
<introduction>
<p>
The amount of water, in gallons, left in a pool
<m>t</m>
hours after it starts being emptied is given by the function
<m>W(t) = 16000 - 2000t</m>
.
</p>
</introduction>
<task workspace="1.5in">
<statement>
<p>
Make a table showing the water left after
<m>0</m>
,
<m>1</m>
,
<m>2</m>
, and
<m>3</m>
hours.
</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
Substituting each value of
<m>t</m>
:
</p>
<tabular>
<row bottom="medium">
<cell>
<m>t</m>
(hours)
</cell>
<cell>
<m>0</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>1</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>2</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>3</m>
</cell>
</row>
<row>
<cell>
<m>W</m>
(gallons)
</cell>
<cell>
<m>16000</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>14000</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>12000</m>
</cell>
<cell>
<m>10000</m>
</cell>
</row>
</tabular>
</answer>
</task>
<task workspace="0.75in">
<statement>
<p>How much water did the pool start with?</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
At
<m>t=0</m>
,
<m>W(0) = 16000 - 2000(0) = 16000</m>
gallons. This is the y-intercept of the function.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
<task workspace="1.5in">
<statement>
<p>When will the pool be empty?</p>
</statement>
<answer>
<p>
The pool is empty when
<m>W(t) = 0</m>
. Solving
<m>0 = 16000 - 2000t</m>
gives
<m>2000t = 16000</m>
, so
<m>t = 8</m>
. The pool will be empty after
<m>8</m>
hours.
</p>
</answer>
</task>
</exercise>
</page>
</worksheet>